{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"55d49918-9c7c-465f-96ec-440d2653fd26","content":"You can download `dotnet-trace` as a **standalone executable** — no SDK needed. Inside the container, run:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\nThen collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU sampling trace (Ctrl+C to stop)\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- For **linux-arm64** containers, replace `linux-x64` with `linux-arm64` in the URL.\n- Copy the `.nettrace` file out with `docker cp` and open it in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [SpeedScope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n- If you can't install tools inside the container, use `docker cp` to copy the binary in: `docker cp dotnet-trace <container>:/tmp/`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"184ffe5c-3568-40be-aa62-34c79c920fe5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling. I can answer this directly from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.\n\nKey points:\n1. `dotnet-trace` is a .NET global tool, but you can also get it as a standalone download (no SDK required).\n2. For .NET 8 on Linux, you can download the single-file version from the dotnet diagnostics releases.\n\n\n3. I can use `curl` to fetch it directly into the container, which is the simplest approach for this scenario.","outputTokens":448,"requestId":"D821:237AB0:343DD20:3913FD1:69FBEAFC"},"id":"f1bdec27-bec8-4372-a2ff-73ec24d78000","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:29:43.855Z","parentId":"59b8c2eb-6b7c-41ea-aa66-b7f8ac87bf62"}
